@Node "I_genr"

	This tab gather all the settings necessary to create html pages.
	The options @{"Thumbnails"  link  "I_Vign"} and  @{"Images"  link  "I_img"} set,
	you may use this tab to create as many pages as you wish.

	- @{B}Root : @{UB}
		Common directory for data.
		Links you will create in your HTML pages will be relative
		to the root.
		
	-@{b}Image directory :@{ub}
		Image Directory.
		Be careful: browsers only diplay gif and jpeg images.
		png format is not yet supported (maybe in a future release).

	-@{b}HTML filenames:@{ub}
		HTML filenames prefix.  (e.g. : pgs would give pgs1.html pgs2.html ...)

	-@{b}Pc format 8+3 filenames :@{ub}
		This option makes HTMLcat truncate all filenames @{b}(on disk!)@{ub}
		in order ot get 8+3 filenames.

	-@{b}Gallery title :@{ub}
		This title appears above the thumbnail table and
		above images (depending on settings)

	-@{b}Use as title :@{ub}

		*@{b}a text@{ub} :
			HTML pages title will be the string specified in
			'gallery title'.

		*@{b}a picture@{ub}:
			HTML pages title will appear as an image.
			This image can be chosen simply by right-clicking
			on 'gallery title'.

	-@{b}Thumbnail  :@{ub}
		Execute the thumbnail-creating script ( Rexx:MKVignettes.rexx )

		This script has to be executed with ADPRO. ADPRO assignment
		has to exist in your system.

		if you wish to create new Arexx scripts, here are few rules
		to follow:

			-  Le nom des fichiers thumbnails est composé de la
			lettre v suivi du nom du fichier d'origine.
			- thumbnail filenames has to be the character "v"
			followed by the former filename

			- Parameters passing :

				1st  param : thumbnail directory
				2nd param : thumbnails height

			- image list is in t:htmlcat12.tmp

			- Send me your scripts for I could add them in
			archive.


	-@{b}HTML :@{ub}
			 Creates HTML files.

		There are three categories of html files:
			- N files img0x.html corresponding to images.
			- P files pimg0y.html corresponding to  
 			  thumbnails pages.
			-  1  fichiers imgp.html which displays the list of
			HTML pages (you may use it in frames).

	 Voir @{" Result " Link "res"}.


@EndNode "I_genr"

@Node "I_vign"

	Here, you'll find all the options relative to the thumbnail pages.

	-@{b}Background image :@{ub}
		Choose the background image for thumbnail pages.

	-@{b}Browsing images and title :@{ub}

		*@{b}Images only@{ub} :
			Displays two images which allows you to go
			through pages (previous & next)
		*@{b}Title Only@{ub} :
			Diplays only the gallery title as a caption for
			thumbnails table.
		*@{b}Both@{ub} :
			Title will be between the "previous" and "next"
			images.

	-@{b}Display :@{ub}

		Affects previous choice.

		*@{b}On top@{ub} :
			Title and/or browsing images will be displayed
			above the thumbnails table.
		*@{b}On bottom@{ub} :
			Title and/or browsing images will be displayed
			below the thumbnails table.			
		*@{b}Both@{ub} :
			Title and/or browsing images will be displayed
			above and below the thumbnails table.		
		*@{b}None@{ub} :
			Title and browsing images won't be displayed.

	-@{b}Previous image :@{ub}
	-@{b}Next image   :@{ub}
		These images define the browsing images.

	-@{b}Show :@{ub}

		*@{b}Thumbnails only@{ub} :
			Only thumbnails will be displayed in the table

		*@{b}Filenames only@{ub} :
			Only image filenames will be displayed.

		*@{b}Both@{ub} :
			Image filenames will be dipslayed below thumbnails.

	-@{b}Use thumbnail files/Use HTML Tags@{ub}

			1. Use thumbnail tags

				The pages containing the thumbnails will
		define links to these files.

			2. Use HTML Tags

                                Thumbnails will be links to image files.
                                Display size will be defined by the flag
                                @{b}hauteur@{ub} and will be applied by
				setting HTML flags @{b}Width@{ub} and
				@{b}Height@{ub}.
				

		WARNING: If you use lbrowse with this option, it won't
	display images in real size when you click on a thumbnail.
	lbrowse load the image file, resizes it in order to display it as
	a thumbnail (width and height). But when you want to display it
	on normal size, it does not refresh its buffer and uses the size
	of the first to display the second.


	-@{b}thumbnail height:@{ub}
		Define thumbnail height (in pixels)

	-@{b}Number of images per page :@{ub}
		Number of thumbnails to display per page.

	-@{b}Number of rows:@{ub}

		Number of rows in the thumbnail table.

	-@{b}Table border width :@{ub}
		Width of the table frame. Sets the paramter "border" of
		the control TABLE".

	-@{b}Default :@{ub}
		Saves settings into the tooltype of the software icon.
		(Same function as "default" button in the "IMAGES" tag.

@EndNode "I_vign"

@Node "I_img"

	This tab inlcudes the options relative to the image pages.

	-@{b}Background color :@{ub}
		Color string format:

			#RRGGBB

		RR,GG,BB : 00 -> FF

	@{b}======================================@{ub}

	-@{b}Browsing images and title :@{ub}
	-@{b}Show :@{ub}			   @{b}See @{"Thumbnails" Link "I_vign"}@{ub}
	-@{b}Previous image :@{ub}
	-@{b}Next Image   :@{ub}

	@{b}======================================@{ub}


	-@{b}Use as title:@{ub}
		*@{b}Filename@{ub} :
			Gives displayed image file name.

		@{b}Gallery title@{ub} :
			Displays gallery title (text or image).

	-@{b}Copy thumbnail settings :@{ub}
		Allows you to create a copy of settings done in the tab
		l'onglet @{"thumbnails" Link "I_vign"}.

	-@{b}Default :@{ub}
		Saves the settings done in software icone's tooltypes.
		(same functions as the "THUMBNAIL" tab)
	
@EndNode "I_img"

@Node res "Result"


	In this part, i'll try and explain the structure I've chosen to create
	html pages.

	Say you've got this directory tree on your partition:


		DH1:
		|____ Software
		|
		|____ Games
		|
		|____ Data
		!	|
		:	|____ Samples
		.	|
		.	|____ Images
		.	!	|
		.	:	|_____ Vallejo
			.	|
			.	|_____ Mangas
			.	|
				|_____ Bellamy
				|
				|_____ HRGiger
				!
				:
				.
				.

	Now let's say you wanna create thumbnails for the directory Vallejo...	

	* The first thing to do is to determine the root directory.
	This directory must contain all image directories, thumbnail directories
	and html pages along with browsing images and background images.

	Let's choose, for instance, DH1:Data/ as root.

	* Gallery title, background and browsing images set, we have to choose
	the image directory.

		In our example :  Images/Vallejo/

	* Now, we may give an nome to our HTML files.
		Let's choose "bv" (for "Boris Vallejo").

	You can now access the "HTML" button...

	* ... click on it!

	HTMLcat will create the directory tree it needs and then create
	all the needed HTML files.

	Let's go back to our previous tree, the root is DH1:Data/

		DH1:
		|____ Software
		|
		|____ Games
		|
		|____ Data
		!	|
		:	|____ Samples
		.	|
		.	|____ Images
		.	!	|
		.	:	|_____ Vallejo
			.	|
			.	|_____ Mangas
			.	|
				|_____ Bellamy
				|
				|_____ HRGiger
				!
				:
				
				

			.
			:
			|____ HTML
			|	|
			|	|_____ Images	
			|		|
			|		|____ Vallejo
			|
			|____ VIGN
			|	|
			|	|_____ Images	
			|		|
			|		|____ Vallejo



	The directories HTML and VIGN has been added to our root.

	In each of these directories, HTMLcat has made a kind of "copy"
	of the tree from the root down to the image directory.

	In HTML/images/Vallejo, we may find the HTML files.
 	In VIGN/images/Vallejo, the scipt has put the thumbnail files.

	* Now, if you want to create thumbnails for the directory Mangas,
	Bellamy or any other directory, the software will add a directory
	Mangas/Bellamy in HTML/images/ and VIGN/images/.


 	Why have I chosen this structure ?
	=======================================

	Good question, thank you for asking.

		The elements the HTML page is made up of are accessed in
	a relative way.
	e.g.  :  to access an image from an html page, the link will be:
		../../../Images/Vallejo/img01.jpg

			pour access thumbnails :

		../../../Vign/images/Vallejo/vimg01.jpg

			pour access the background image :

		../../../fond.jpg 

	The advantage with the structure I have chosen is that you may
	redefine the whole tree on top of your root without affecting
	the strucure of your pages. Of course, you have to define your 
	root carefully.


@EndNode res
